(1, 'Chicken Katsu Curry', 'Wagamama inspired Katsu Curry', 'Japanese chicken curry', 'katsu.jpg', '1.   Blend 2 tbsp sunflower oil, 2 onions, 5 garlic cloves, 2 carrots, 2 tbsp plain flour, 4 tsp curry powder, 600ml chicken stock, 2 tsp honey, 4 tsp soy sauce, 1 bay leaf, and 1 tsp garam masala to make the curry sauce.\r\n2.   Heat for 10-12 minutes over a low heat.\r\n3.   Simmer for 20 minutes until it thickens.\r\n4.   For the chicken, season with salt and pepper, coat in flour, then a beaten egg, and finally in Panko breadcrumbs all over.\r\n5.   Shallow fry for 10 minutes.', '<ol>\n<li>Blend 2 tbsp sunflower oil, 2 onions, 5 garlic cloves, 2 carrots, 2 tbsp plain flour, 4 tsp curry powder, 600ml chicken stock, 2 tsp honey, 4 tsp soy sauce, 1 bay leaf, and 1 tsp garam masala to make the curry sauce.</li>\n<li>Heat for 10-12 minutes over a low heat.</li>\n<li>Simmer for 20 minutes until it thickens.</li>\n<li>For the chicken, season with salt and pepper, coat in flour, then a beaten egg, and finally in Panko breadcrumbs all over.</li>\n<li>Shallow fry for 10 minutes.</li>\n</ol>\n', 'We found the recipe relatively straightforward and easy to follow. We think you could even blitz the veg instead of sieving it to minimise waste. To get that iconic Wagamama rice dome, pack the rice into a suitably sized bowl that has been lightly coated with oil. Place a plate on top of it, then turn it all over so the bowl is now upside-down, then remove the bowl slowly (you may have to give it a slight tap).\r\n\r\nOverall the meal was delicious however the chicken can be a little greasy. It is definitely worth padding it with kitchen paper to absorb any excess. Having tried the original Wagamama recipe, this is an extremely close recipe. Enjoy!\r\n\r\n![alt text here](/MyCMS/img/katsu.jpg "Title here")\r\n<p class="caption" markdown="1">So easy, and fast!</p>', '<p>We found the recipe relatively straightforward and easy to follow. We think you could even blitz the veg instead of sieving it to minimise waste. To get that iconic Wagamama rice dome, pack the rice into a suitably sized bowl that has been lightly coated with oil. Place a plate on top of it, then turn it all over so the bowl is now upside-down, then remove the bowl slowly (you may have to give it a slight tap).</p>\n\n<p>Overall the meal was delicious however the chicken can be a little greasy. It is definitely worth padding it with kitchen paper to absorb any excess. Having tried the original Wagamama recipe, this is an extremely close recipe. Enjoy!</p>\n\n<img src="/MyCMS/img/katsu.jpg" alt="alt text here" title="Title here" />\n\n<p class="caption">So easy, and fast!</p>\n', '2015-01-18 12:01:53'),
(2, 'Three Sauce Chicken Thighs', 'Chicken thighs marinated in three different chilli sauces', 'chicken chilli sauce gochujang', '3-sauce-wings.jpg', '', '', '# Three Sauce Chicken Thighs\r\nThis is an ideal recipe for the post Christmas lull when you need to use up some left over meat. The chilli sauces will also banish those winter blues by providing some much needed heat!\r\n\r\n###Ingredients\r\n**chicken:**\r\n\r\n* Chicken thighs\r\n* Plain flour\r\n* Salt and pepper\r\n\r\n**sauces:**\r\n\r\n* 3 tbsp gochujang\r\n* 3 shallots\r\n* 3 tbsp soy sauce\r\n* 1 garlic clove\r\n* Thumb sized piece of peeled ginger\r\n* 2 tsp rice wine vinegar\r\n* [Frank''s&#174; Buffalo Wings Sauce](http://www.franksredhot.com/products/buffalo-wings-sauce/)\r\n* 1 tbsp honey\r\n* BBQ sauce\r\n\r\n### Method\r\n1. Mix salt and pepper in the flour and coat the thighs thoroughly.\r\n2. Place in the oven for 20 mins.\r\n3. Blend the gochujang, shallots, soy, garlic, ginger, and rice wine vinegar for the gochujan sauce.\r\n4. Heat some Frank''s hot sauce in a pan and add the honey for the second sauce.\r\n5. Place some BBQ sauce in a bowl for the third sauce.\r\n6. When the chicken is sizzling and brown, coat the thighs with the three sauces using a basting brush.\r\n7. Add back to the oven for 10-12 mins to crisp up.\r\n\r\n### Sauce one - Gochujang\r\n[Gochujang](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gochujang "Gochujang Wikipedia article") is a Korean red chilli paste, it adds a nice kick to any marinade without being too hot. Although not particularly common here in the UK, it can be found in specialist food outlets, or [online](http://www.amazon.co.uk/Daesang-Sunchang-Gochujang-Pepper-500g/dp/B002WTE0MQ "Buy Gochujang at Amazon") (we got ours from a local Chinese supermarket). The taste of Gochujang is very strong, so the other ingredients were added to try and temper the mix.\r\n\r\n### Sauce two - Hot Toddy\r\nThis sauce takes a popular wing sauce and makes it seasonal by adding some honey. This gives it a nice medicinal feeling which hits the spot at this time of year.\r\n\r\n### Sauce three - BBQ\r\nWe were that hungry by now that for the third sauce we just used a bottle of readily available BBQ sauce!\r\n\r\nJust letting the chicken catch slightly gave the marinades a nice charred taste which added to the flavour. Using thighs with the skin on also added to an overall better taste.', '<p class="phil">This is an ideal recipe for the post Christmas lull when you need to use up some left over meat. The chilli sauces will also banish those winter blues by providing some much needed heat!</p>\r\n<h3>Sauce one - Gochujang</h3>\r\n<p class="pete"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gochujang" title="Gochujang Wikipedia article">Gochujang</a> is a Korean red chilli paste, it adds a nice kick to any marinade without being too hot. Although not particularly common here in the UK, it can be found in specialist food outlets, or <a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/Daesang-Sunchang-Gochujang-Pepper-500g/dp/B002WTE0MQ" title="Buy Gochujang at Amazon">online</a> (we got ours from a local Chinese supermarket). The taste of Gochujang is very strong, so the other ingredients were added to try and temper the mix.</p>\r\n<h3>Sauce two - Hot Toddy</h3>\r\n<p class="phil">This sauce takes a popular wing sauce and makes it seasonal by adding some honey. This gives it a nice medicinal feeling which hits the spot at this time of year.</p>\r\n<h3>Sauce three - BBQ</h3>\r\n<p class="pete">We were that hungry by now that for the third sauce we just used a bottle of readily available BBQ sauce!</p>\r\n<p class="phil">Just letting the chicken catch slightly gave the marinades a nice charred taste which added to the flavour. Using thighs with the skin on also added to an overall better taste.</p>', '2015-01-18 17:56:01'),
(6, 'Ciabatta Pizza', 'Even quicker cheats pizza', 'pizza', '', '', '', '#Ciabatta Pizza', '<h1>Ciabatta Pizza</h1>', '2015-03-07 16:48:45'),
(7, 'Creme Fraiche Pasta', 'A creamy pasta sauce with creme fraiche', 'pasta creme fraiche', 'creme-fraiche-pasta.jpg', '', '', '#Creme Fraiche Pasta Sauce\r\n', '<p class="phil">This is a great recipe to use up some left over veg.</p>', '2015-03-07 17:02:59'),
(8, 'Bulgogi Beef Sandwich', 'A Korean American mash up', 'beef gochujang cheesesteak sandwich', 'placeholder.jpg', '1.   Season beef and place in oven at mark 5 for 40 minutes.\r\n2.   Blend 2 tbsp of Gochujang with 2 tbsp of soy, 1 tbsp rice wine vinegar, and 2 cloves of garlic.\r\n3.   Fry off a couple of peppers, carrots and onions.\r\n4.   Place sub or baguette in oven.\r\n5.   Shred beef and mix into sauce.\r\n6.   Fill subs, lay over some Emmenthal cheese and place back in oven until it has melted.', '<ol>\r\n<li>Season beef and place in oven at mark 5 for 40 minutes.</li>\r\n<li>Blend 2 tbsp of Gochujang with 2 tbsp of soy, 1 tbsp rice wine vinegar, and 2 cloves of garlic.</li>\r\n<li>Fry off a couple of peppers, carrots and onions.</li>\r\n<li>Place sub or baguette in oven.</li>\r\n<li>Shred beef and mix into sauce.</li>\r\n<li>Fill subs, lay over some Emmenthal cheese and place back in oven until it has melted.</li>\r\n</ol>', 'There are few things in life more satisfying to a hungry man than a good sandwich. Imagine then, the solemn joy that is induced when that hungry man stumbles across a ''worldy'' of a sandwich like the filthy Bulgogi pulled beef beast.\r\n\r\n<p class="peter">I concur. This is how I imagine a fusion of Korean and American street vendor food to look. The Philly cheese-steak sandwich slapped right in the face with explosive Korean flavour.</p>\r\n\r\nIt''s shaped like a torpedo and the flavour it packs is just as powerful. Like all good sandwich fillings it''s simple. Slow cooked pulled beef that is then mixed with a sauce that deserves statues in its honour. The main ingredient to the sauce is Gochujang, which is then added to with soy sauce, rice wine vinegar, and a little seasoning. The resulting sauce is infinitely more remarkable than the sum of its parts. A wonderful punch of fruity flavour that borders on the obscene is laced with a well-meaning kick of spice. Reliving the flavour in my minds-mouth is making me question whether I''ve stumbled across a food that transcends this 4 dimensional world of ours and gives its consumer a brief insight to the 5th dimension. If there''s ever a Nobel prize for sarnies, the inventor of Bulgogi surely gets my vote.\r\n\r\nA fresh baked sub roll that''s still warm when filled to bursting with the beef and topped with Emmenthal and grilled immediately before serving....BOOM!\r\n![bulgogi beef sandwich](/MyCMS/img/Bulgogi-Cheesesteak-Sandwich.jpg "Bulgogi Beef Sandwich")\r\n\r\n*[''worldy'']: Other-worldly, ethereal, outstanding.', '<p class="phil">There are few things in life more satisfying to a hungry man than a good sandwich. Imagine then, the solemn joy that is induced when that \r\n                    hungry man stumbles across a <abbr title="from another world, ethereal">worldy</abbr> of a sandwich like the filthy bulgogi pulled beef beast.</p>\r\n\r\n                <p class="pete">I concur. I like the combination of cultures with this sandwich. The classic American cheesesteak combined with far eastern spice. I''m romanticising \r\n                    about how this should be common street food in all major cities.</p>\r\n\r\n                <p class="phil">It''s shaped like a torpedo and the flavour it packs is just as powerful. Like all good sandwich fillings it''s simple. Slow cooked, pulled beef that \r\n                    is then mixed with a sauce that deserves statues in its honour. The main ingredient to the sauce is <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gochujang">Gochujang</a>, \r\n                    which is then added to with soy sauce, rice wine vinegar, and a little seasoning. The resulting sauce is infinitely more remarkable than the sum of its parts. A wonderful punch of fruity \r\n                    flavour that borders upon the obscene is laced with a well-meaning kick of spice. Reliving the flavor in my minds-mouth is making me question whether \r\n                    I''ve stumbled across a food that transcends this 4 dimensional world of ours and gives its consumer a brief insight to the 5th dimension. If there''s \r\n                    ever a Nobel prize for sarnies, the inventor of Bulgogi surely gets my vote.</p>\r\n\r\n                <p class="pete">That might be due to adding too much Gochujang. Surprisingly there is no warning on the container that suggests a visit to a higher dimension if the \r\n                    recommended dosage is exceeded. For info, our recommended dosage is 2 tablespoons. I haven''t spotted Gochujang in the supermarkets but it is available at your local \r\n                    Chinese supermarket if you have one. I''d highly recommend a trip if you do, they are a fantastic source of food that you can''t get anywhere else, plus you can get a nice \r\n                    warm feeling inside for supporting a local business.</p>\r\n\r\n                <p class="phil">To finish off, a fresh baked sub roll that''s still warm when filled to bursting with the beef and topped with Emmenthal and grilled immediately before serving...BOOM!</p>\r\n\r\n                <p class="pete">For the effort involved, the taste is phenomenal. If there were such an effort-to-taste ratio this would be up there (or down there.....this needs more thought). Fry off \r\n                    some veg to fill the sandwich out, such as peppers, carrots or onions, or all 3.</p>\r\n\r\n<img src="/MyCMS/img/Bulgogi-Cheesesteak-Sandwich.jpg" alt="bulgogi beef sandwich" title="Bulgogi Beef Sandwich" />\r\n<p class="caption">Paste some Bulgogi sauce onto the bread before baking to maximise the taste.</p>\r\n', '2015-03-13 11:35:55'),
(11, 'Pizza al forno', 'A quick, authentic Italian pizza', 'Italian pizza', 'pizza-al-forno-zoomed.jpg', '1.   For the base, mix 240g of flour with a little salt and small amounts of water until it binds.\r\n2.   For the sauce, blend a tin of chopped tomatoes with a handful of basil, 2 garlic cloves, a lug of olive oil and a splash of balsamic.\r\n3.   Roll the base and place it in a pan with a lug of oil on a medium heat.\r\n4.   Pour over the sauce (there will be some left).\r\n5.   Tear over pieces of Mozzarella.\r\n6.   Grate over some Parmesan.\r\n7.   Add other toppings to suit your taste. We added salami, fennel, a de-seeded chilli and black olives.\r\n8.   When the base is golden, place under the grill for 5 minutes to finish off the toppings.', '<ol>\r\n<li>For the base, mix 240g of flour with a little salt and small amounts of water until it binds.</li>\r\n<li>For the sauce, blend a tin of chopped tomatoes with a handful of basil, 2 garlic cloves, a lug of olive oil and a splash of balsamic.</li>\r\n<li>Roll the base and place it in a pan with a lug of oil on a medium heat.</li>\r\n<li>Pour over the sauce (there will be some left).</li>\r\n<li>Tear over pieces of Mozzarella.</li>\r\n<li>Grate over some Parmesan.</li>\r\n<li>Add other toppings to suit your taste. We added salami, fennel, a de-seeded chilli and black olives.</li>\r\n<li>When the base is golden, place under the grill for 5 minutes to finish off the toppings.</li>\r\n</ol>', '<p class="phil">This is a very good recipe for those in a rush, and you can impress your friends by making everything including the sauce and dough.</p>\r\n<p class="pete">Put the telephone down and step away from the takeaway menu! As soon as you try this recipe once you will never go back, I promise.</p>\r\n<p class="phil">We fry the dough off underneath to make it sturdy, ready to receive the toppings. We then finish it off under the grill to do the rest. Quick and easy, although not like a mamma used to make.</p>\r\n<p class="pete">The sauce can be quickly made using a blender. Once this and the dough are done, you can get the fun part, the toppings!</p>\r\n![pizza al forno with olives and feta](/MyCMS/img/pizza-al-forno-good.jpg "pizza al forno with olives and feta")\r\n<p class="caption">We went a little crazy with this one. It has mozzarella, parmesan, salami, fennell, a red chilli, chestnut mushrooms, olives, and feta.</p>\r\n<p class="phil">You will be amazed with the taste. Although it is trying to be as authentic as possible, it isn''t trying too hard. Therefore it has its own unique flavour, which I think is much better than any takeaway could offer.</p>\r\n<p class="pete">And much cheaper. We are thinking of you.</p>\r\n![pizza al forno](/MyCMS/img/pizza-al-forno.jpg "Pizza al forno")\r\n<p class="caption">You can have too many toppings. This is back to basics with just tomato, mozzarella and basil.</p>', '<p class="phil">This is a very good recipe for those in a rush, and you can impress your friends by making everything including the sauce and dough.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="pete">Put the telephone down and step away from the takeaway menu! As soon as you try this recipe once you will never go back, I promise.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="phil">We fry the dough off underneath to make it sturdy, ready to receive the toppings. We then finish it off under the grill to do the rest. Quick and easy, although not like a mamma used to make.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="pete">The sauce can be quickly made using a blender. Once this and the dough are done, you can get the fun part, the toppings!</p>\r\n\r\n<img src="/MyCMS/img/pizza-al-forno-good.jpg" alt="pizza al forno with olives and feta" title="pizza al forno with olives and feta" />\r\n\r\n<p class="caption">We went a little crazy with this one. It has mozzarella, parmesan, salami, fennell, a red chilli, chestnut mushrooms, olives, and feta.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="phil">You will be amazed with the taste. Although it is trying to be as authentic as possible, it isn''t trying too hard. Therefore it has its own unique flavour, which I think is much better than any takeaway could offer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="pete">And much cheaper. We are thinking of you.</p>\r\n\r\n<img src="/MyCMS/img/pizza-al-forno.jpg" alt="pizza al forno" title="Pizza al forno" />\r\n\r\n<p class="caption">You can have too many toppings. This is back to basics with just tomato, mozzarella and basil.</p>\r\n', '2015-05-05 20:31:28'),
(12, 'Quesa-enchi-rrito', 'A homemade ensemble of Quesadillas, Enchiladas, and Burritos', 'Mexican beef tortillas', 'slices-of-quesadillas.jpg', '1.   Fry 500g of good quality steak mince with a couple of garlic cloves.\r\n2.   When browning add 2 sliced peppers, and a handful of chopped mushrooms.\r\n3.   Add 300ml of passata and mix.\r\n4.   Place 4 tortillas in the oven to warm up.\r\n5.   When ready, place the mix between the tortillas and sprinkle over some cheese, on the mix and on top of the tortillas.\r\n6.   Place back in the oven until the cheese melts.', '<ol>\n<li>Fry 500g of good quality steak mince with a couple of garlic cloves.</li>\n<li>When browning add 2 sliced peppers, and a handful of chopped mushrooms.</li>\n<li>Add 300ml of passata and mix.</li>\n<li>Place 4 tortillas in the oven to warm up.</li>\n<li>When ready, place the mix between the tortillas and sprinkle over some cheese, on the mix and on top of the tortillas.</li>\n<li>Place back in the oven until the cheese melts.</li>\n</ol>\n', '<p class="phil">We have no idea if this is a Quesadilla, Enchilada, or Burrito, but the taste is excellent.</p>\r\n<p class="pete">I hope we are not compounding our ignorance by saying that. Maybe someone can let us know in the comments!</p>\r\n<p class="phil">If you like more of a kick, add a chilli or three, we added some tabasco sauce in lieu of the chillis.</p>\r\n<p class="pete">People complain that Tabasco is merely there to add heat, not flavour, but I think once you get used to more heat in your food you can appreciate the flavour. It definitely added to the flavour and a nice lingering heat on the tongue, just to convince you that you are eating spicy Mexican food!</p>\r\n<p class="phil">Overall this is an extremely easy recipe. After you have experimented with your preferred combinations, you could easily smash this out in 15 minutes.</p>', '<p class="phil">We have no idea if this is a Quesadilla, Enchilada, or Burrito, but the taste is excellent.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="pete">I hope we are not compounding our ignorance by saying that. Maybe someone can let us know in the comments!</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="phil">If you like more of a kick, add a chilli or three, we added some tabasco sauce in lieu of the chillis.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="pete">People complain that Tabasco is merely there to add heat, not flavour, but I think once you get used to more heat in your food you can appreciate the flavour. It definitely added to the flavour and a nice lingering heat on the tongue, just to convince you that you are eating spicy Mexican food!</p>\r\n<p class="phil">Overall this is an extremely easy recipe. After you have experimented with your preferred combinations, you could easily smash this out in 15 minutes.</p>\r\n', '2015-05-09 13:25:33'),
(13, 'Chicken and noodles', 'Five spice chicken with a fiery noodle dressing', 'chicken noodles five-spice', 'satay-chickay.jpg', '1.   Season chicken breasts with salt and pepper, and coat with five spice\r\n2.   Oil a pan and place chicken in over a medium heat\r\n3.   For the dressing, blend together half a red onion, a chilli, juice of 1 lime, 3-4 tbsp olive oil, 2 tbsp soy, 1 tsp sesame oil, 1 tsp fish sauce, and a bunch of coriander stalks\r\n4.   Warm a pan with a little oil ready for the nuts\r\n5.   Boil the kettle and get the noodles cooking\r\n6.   Add a pack of cashews to the hot pan. When brown, coat with honey and toss in some sesame seeds\r\n7.   When chicken is nearly cooked, coat with sweet chilli sauce and sesame seeds\r\n8.   Drain noodles and mix with the dressing and nuts. Add an optional chilli and coriander\r\n9.   Slice chicken and serve with noodles. Sprinkle coriander on top to serve', '<ol>\n<li>Season chicken breasts with salt and pepper, and coat with five spice</li>\n<li>Oil a pan and place chicken in over a medium heat</li>\n<li>For the dressing, blend together half a red onion, a chilli, juice of 1 lime, 3-4 tbsp olive oil, 2 tbsp soy, 1 tsp sesame oil, 1 tsp fish sauce, and a bunch of coriander stalks</li>\n<li>Warm a pan with a little oil ready for the nuts</li>\n<li>Boil the kettle and get the noodles cooking</li>\n<li>Add a pack of cashews to the hot pan. When brown, coat with honey and toss in some sesame seeds</li>\n<li>When chicken is nearly cooked, coat with sweet chilli sauce and sesame seeds</li>\n<li>Drain noodles and mix with the dressing and nuts. Add an optional chilli and coriander</li>\n<li>Slice chicken and serve with noodles. Sprinkle coriander on top to serve</li>\n</ol>\n', '<p class="pete">This is an extremely tasty recipe. It is a twist on a far eastern satay recipe, where instead of a peanut sauce, five spice is used to marinate the chicken. The zesty noodle dressing stays honest to its roots by providing the kick.</p>\r\n<p class="phil">Its got more kick than a mule whose just spotted a rotund beach goer approaching! Don''t be afraid to stray from the recipe to get the dressing just to your liking.</p>\r\n<p class="pete">Get the pan for the nuts nice and hot before adding them to get a nice browning to them.</p>\r\n<p class="phil">We used medium egg noodles. They provide a nice thick noodle to soak up the lovely dressing.</p>\r\n<p class="pete">The dressing is good for any dish. We may tackle the satay sauce next, which will also work with this dressing. It is very versatile.</p>\r\n![satay chicken](/MyCMS/img/satay-chickay.jpg "satay chicken and noodles")\r\n<p class="caption">The final result</p>', '<p class="pete">This is an extremely tasty recipe. It is a twist on a far eastern satay recipe, where instead of a peanut sauce, five spice is used to marinate the chicken. The zesty noodle dressing stays honest to its roots by providing the kick.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="phil">Its got more kick than a mule whose just spotted a rotund beach goer approaching! Don''t be afraid to stray from the recipe to get the dressing just to your liking.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="pete">Get the pan for the nuts nice and hot before adding them to get a nice browning to them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="phil">We used medium egg noodles. They provide a nice thick noodle to soak up the lovely dressing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="pete">The dressing is good for any dish. We may tackle the satay sauce next, which will also work with this dressing. It is very versatile.</p>\r\n\r\n<img src="/MyCMS/img/satay-chickay.jpg" alt="satay chicken" title="satay chicken and noodles" />\r\n\r\n<p class="caption">The final result</p>\r\n', '2015-05-16 15:55:34'),
(15, 'Pork Fennel Ragu', 'A heartwarming traditional pork and fennel pasta', 'Italian pork fennel pasta', 'pork-ragu.jpg', '1.   Blend 3/4 carrots, 2/3 spring onions, 1/2 sticks of celery and a red chilli\r\n2.   Add to a pan on a high heat\r\n3.   Blend 5 high quality pork sausages with a tsp of fennel seeds and a tsp of oregano\r\n4.   Add to pan and brown the meat\r\n5.   Add 3/4 crushed garlic cloves and 4 tbsp of balsamic vinegar\r\n6.  Add a tin of chopped tomatoes. Fill the tin with water and add to the pan\r\n7.   Boil the kettle and get the pasta cooking\r\n8.   When the ragu has reduced, add the cooked pasta and mix\r\n9.   Add a handful of chopped basil and sprinkle over Parmesan to serve', '<ol>\n<li>Blend 3/4 carrots, 2/3 spring onions, 1/2 sticks of celery and a red chilli</li>\n<li>Add to a pan on a high heat</li>\n<li>Blend 5 high quality pork sausages with a tsp of fennel seeds and a tsp of oregano</li>\n<li>Add to pan and brown the meat</li>\n<li>Add 3/4 crushed garlic cloves and 4 tbsp of balsamic vinegar</li>\n<li>Add a tin of chopped tomatoes. Fill the tin with water and add to the pan</li>\n<li>Boil the kettle and get the pasta cooking</li>\n<li>When the ragu has reduced, add the cooked pasta and mix</li>\n<li>Add a handful of chopped basil and sprinkle over Parmesan to serve</li>\n</ol>\n', '<p class="phil" markdown="1">We love this dish. It feels like authentic homemade Italian food and is sure to warm the cockles.</p>\r\n<p class="pete" markdown="1">Indeed. It is a useful recipe to use up veg, and can be a real fiery affair if you add more or stronger chillis. But do not attempt without a blender.</p>\r\n<p class="phil" markdown="1">I don''t even know how you''d tackle it without one, especially for the sausages.</p>\r\n<p class="pete" markdown="1">It is a dish that likes to motor along on a high heat, so don''t be afraid to turn the hob right up. Even when the sauce is bubbling along like [Grotbag''s](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grotbags "Grotbags-Wikipedia") cauldron, just put the lid on.</p>\r\n<p class="pete" markdown="1">Squashing the tomato chunks injects a jolt of flavour into the sauce, but don''t worry about getting them all, a juicy tomato chunk in the gob makes a nice surprise every now and again.</p>\r\n<p class="phil" markdown="1">Also, be sure to save some of the pasta water. There is a tendency for the pasta to dry up when you add it to the ragu, to the indignation of a million Italian nonnas. So add the water to the mix to prevent this from happening.</p>\r\n![pork fennel pasta](/MyCMS/img/pork-ragu.jpg "Pork and Fennel Pasta")\r\n<p class="caption" markdown="1">Ignore the tarts for now. We promise to write about these soon!</p>\r\n\r\n*[gob]: Mouth. Not pronounced jobe for all you Arrested Development fans.', '<p class="phil">We love this dish. It feels like authentic homemade Italian food and is sure to warm the cockles.</p>\n\n<p class="pete">Indeed. It is a useful recipe to use up veg, and can be a real fiery affair if you add more or stronger chillis. But do not attempt without a blender.</p>\n\n<p class="phil">I don''t even know how you''d tackle it without one, especially for the sausages.</p>\n\n<p class="pete">It is a dish that likes to motor along on a high heat, so don''t be afraid to turn the hob right up. Even when the sauce is bubbling along like <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grotbags" title="Grotbags-Wikipedia">Grotbag''s</a> cauldron, just put the lid on.</p>\n\n<p class="pete">Squashing the tomato chunks injects a jolt of flavour into the sauce, but don''t worry about getting them all, a juicy tomato chunk in the <abbr title="Mouth. Not pronounced jobe for all you Arrested Development fans.">gob</abbr> makes a nice surprise every now and again.</p>\n\n<p class="phil">Also, be sure to save some of the pasta water. There is a tendency for the pasta to dry up when you add it to the ragu, to the indignation of a million Italian nonnas. So add the water to the mix to prevent this from happening.</p>\n\n<img src="/MyCMS/img/pork-ragu.jpg" alt="pork fennel pasta" title="Pork and Fennel Pasta" />\n\n<p class="caption">Ignore the tarts for now. We promise to write about these soon!</p>\n', '2015-05-17 11:51:43');

